
**File 1 — the HTTP client config

Stop creating the client once when the file loads. Right now it builds a single shared client at module load and exports that one instance. Change it so the client is created on demand by a function instead. That function should: read the auth cookie at the moment it's called, build a fresh client, set the auth token as a default header on that client, attach the existing request and response interceptors, and return it. Remove the old shared-instance creation and the default export of that instance. The function needs to be async, because reading the cookie is now done inside it.

The key shift: the token is read *inside this function* — which runs in request context — instead of inside the interceptor, which doesn't.

**File 2 — the interceptor utility 

Take the token reading out of the request interceptor entirely. Remove its dependency on the token-reading helper, and remove the line that builds the authorization header. The interceptor should now only set the content-type header and return. The token no longer comes from here — it's already on the client as a default header (from File 1), so the interceptor doesn't need to touch it. Leave the response interceptor as is.

**File 3 — every place that makes an API call

Each of these currently imports the shared client and calls methods on it directly. Change each one to import the new factory function instead, call it (awaiting it) to get a client, then make the request on that returned client. The change is the same in every file: get the client from the function, then use it — rather than using the imported shared instance. These are all server-side files already, which is why this works: calling the factory there gives the cookie read a real request to attach to.

**File 4 — the token-reading helper

No change needed; it's already correct. If you added the temporary cookie-listing debug line earlier, take it out. The helper itself stays for any auth-gating that relies on it.

**Leave alone for now:** the base URL setup and the TLS-verification environment variable. Neither is part of this bug, and the URL is already resolving correctly.

**Why this holds up:** all the token logic now lives in the one factory function. Any future API call that uses the factory gets authentication automatically, so there's nothing per-call to forget — unlike threading the token through all sites by hand.
